Here are some pictures taken during the experiment that I took part of at the University of Nantes with Bio-mechanic research engineer @aureliesarcher for the @drumsbiomech project. 

This is the FIRST scientific research on drum technique, and is a huge breakthrough for the drumming community, because with this research we will start to understand what can happen to our body, if we can develop any musculoskeletal disorder in the long run by developing bad motions and using wrong parts of the body while playing drums! I'm very excited for this, because I saw the amount of data and information they are taking and the incredible research they are doing here. This research will clarify so many open discussions about feet technique, posture etc... 

Next week I will be posting a video in which I talk about what we did, what the research is about and will show some footage of the experiment. Make sure to follow this project, it's as awesome as it looks from these pictures!

GOLIATH was recorded at JFD Studio in Dallas, TX and Studio City, CA as well as The Cabin in Orlando, FL by J-F Dagenais, who also produced and engineered the album. For the mixing and mastering, the band returned to Chris Clancy with assistance from Colin Richardson.

The cover artwork required an image that captured the iconic battle of David versus Goliath, a theme that is echoed throughout the album while matching the power of the music. The band handed the reigns to renown Berlin metal illustrator Eliran Kantor (Testament, Fleshgod Apocalypse) who took the KATAKLYSM look and gave it a macabre filter that compliments the brooding sense of uneasiness that was felt during the writing and recording of the album.

“Blood is seeping through the walls, despair engulfs the souls, the screams are frozen in time. The darkness within, no time to repent, awaken the gods of fire...” 🔥

Good technique = less strength and physical effort!

If you will push physically with strength to play fast you will increase the probability of hurting yourself. That’s why we develop techniques, to use our body and gear in a more efficient way.

Most drummers will ignore this exercise because it seems a simple an irrelevant workout. In reality, the secret behind this exercise is the fact of learning to FOLLOW the sticks with our hands and arms instead of lifting them. This is commonly called the Free Stroke exercise, is what is often also called “bouncing a ball”. This is what we should be doing also at 260, 280, 300 etc... bpm, and it starts from here!

As we know, posture is one of the most important things when it comes to drums and drummers. The leg extension determines how much we stretch and how much we contract our muscles, but how much we open our legs and we distance our feet and pedals is also very important. Let’s see in this video what the data taken from the Bio-mechanic research ongoing at the University of Nantes in France is telling us about this!

Often overlooked in drumming discussions is the vital aspect of sound quality. Picture this: what if we could draw precise lines in the air with the tips of our drumsticks? How accurate would your drumming be—100%, 80%, or a mere 20%? Sadly, many drummers struggle with a mere 20% consistency between strokes. The good news is, there are practical ways to significantly enhance your precision, and I’ll be sharing these valuable insights in this video!

Do you want to develop the most powerful bass drum strokes? The Flat Foot technique will be the best approach you can use to be able to have incredible volume and dynamic on your bass drum while not having to use a lot of effort or strength. Actually, this technique is the foot version of the "whipping motion" used for the hands. With this technique you will have the most relaxed body motions to create the most powerful and controlled stroke we can have on our bass drums.
